##In this series | shadows begin far away, then close, and end up with everyone

Tmagazinechina

Function description, record the changing global cultural landscape

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Starting today, we will be covering the national epidemic for two weeks.

Since 20 January, when new pneumonia entered full public view, the editorial department, in addition to keeping a close eye on the epidemic and its human tragicomedy, has also tried to put it in perspective, a small slice of the disaster that almost erased the national mood in 2019. In the end, we chose 6"personal histories" and 5"text rereads" to form this series. On the former, whether it is the young people who suffer from different degree of epidemic disease after returning home, although they keep a safe distance from the new pneumonia, they also inevitably get involved in it, and experience the horror of it with their whole body Or as a self-financing rock band frontman, as a result of a sense of responsibility, of a sense of reason and passion, of a sense of distrust, of ordinary people who were promptly isolated and healed, in their own way, they are trying to record their dramatic psychological trajectory, and what they see as the capillary of today's China. A group of writers, some professional journalists, some lawyers, some young women new to the job who never thought to write their own stories, they see the suffering (even just one of it) of this generation in the epidemic, but they also depict faces that have kept the dignity of man, the order of life, and the sense of belonging within them as they have fallen apart. We thank them for joining us.

As for the latter, our writers will use the classic texts to ponder the metaphors and uncertainties of the pneumonia epidemic and to discuss the collective state of mind, to admire what Borges called the most important quality of writing -- The heroism. The poet Boris Pasternak once described it in February as a time when "there was enough ink to cry" , but rather than cry, we tend to give the spring of 2020 a reason, so it doesn't burn up in a black flame. It should look like spring.

Compared with our colleagues in the media on the front line, what we have done is really trivial. But as we said on Weibo on New Year's Eve, we hope the Chinese version of t is not absent: This is the way we are not absent, and this is the way we do not forget. Today's push is a "personal account" of a Lucky Wuhan man thanking himself and his family for their "escape from the jaws of death" , although all this is only temporary.

I returned to Wuhan on January 19th, wearing a black non-woven mask. It was useless, but it was better than nothing. The carriages were Sardines as food, but the sardines were naked, and so were the crowds as they got off the train. My mother came to pick me up, a fearless face exposed in the air, angry, think things should not be this way.

On this day, Wuhan residents still do not have the knowledge to prevent COVID-19 pneumonia, we go about as usual, engaged in production and labor. The reason is not listed here, the table is endless. Anyway, I spent a lot of energy fighting with my parents, trying to convince them to take it seriously, and at one point I had a sore throat, and I didn't know why I was hurting myself so much, because I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was -- I was. Urgent from the right, 20, I dragged my cousin under the command of my mother to the drugstore to buy masks, the last 8 medical surgical masks in the store package round. My mother also thought I was overreacting and asked the clerk, are there a lot of people buying masks these days?

The clerk shook his head.

She looks at me like she's a winner.

Of course you can't buy a mask now. My cousin is the first alert of the Group of people, early prepared N95, and the timely relief of a family of five. On the 22nd, when we met for the last time years ago, we canceled our New Year's greetings and exchanged information about hand sanitizer and hand sanitizer, which were also hard to get. He went to the supermarket, raked the shelves on various online platforms, told his stubborn father to wear a mask 10,000 times, never tired of it, and had a much better temper than me. It's reassuring to have someone like that in the house. He unconsciously took on the responsibility of taking care of the whole family, and into the details of shopping, driving to the family to send masks, the car was also hit.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
That day is our family's traditional stock day. New Year is nothing more than fried meatballs, Fried Lotus root folder and other things, this year do less, think no one New Year; wait until no food to eat when they regret how not to do a little more, "cat ears" are not fried, hell. It was also the day that our family finally came to an understanding of "the new Crown" : People would die. Thanks to academician Zhong Nanshan, the people of Wuhan are really beginning to wake up. The next day my dad voluntarily went to the drugstore and bought a box of 50 surgical masks. This is the last box of masks we've bought so far.

First the lack of supplies, then the anxiety. The number of confirmed cases shot up, gobbling them up from province to province. I was still awake when the news of the Wuhan siege was sent out, and I couldn't tell what I was feeling on my cell phone. Had I known it would come to this, I would have been strangely calm: it was a distant thing, but it was happening right now. That split holds me up in the air, wondering where I'll end up. My mother couldn't sleep, so she kept asking me to sleep. I told her Wuhan was closed.

She said, "AH! ". Half an hour later she came to my room: Where did you get the message?

I held up my phone for her to see. She squinted for a moment and said nothing.

When we watched the Spring Festival gala at home on the eve of the Lunar New Year, I felt as if I were in a trance. I felt that there were two worlds in television and reality. Everything was completely quiet. One night when I was lying in bed, I felt something was wrong. On second thought, there was no car in the street.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The real question comes up. The price of vegetables has gone up, of course, but I dare not go out to buy fruit and count oranges. Everyone was trying to figure out how many days they had in stock and when they would have to go out and restock. Aunt call video chat, said your uncle eat too much! If you ask him to eat less for dinner and then have a late supper, you might as well not have dinner at all! I thought to myself, this is a real belt-tightening.

My cousin went out and bought a re-up and bought 900 yuan at one go. What can you buy for $900?

I said he had hot pot. He was happy.

We are the luckiest of people, and our problems are the same: boredom, inability to walk, skipping meals, nothing more. Compared with the really hard, really hard people, our complaints are almost a luxury complaints. There was another episode of my fever, a low fever, a dry cough, and the whole family was so tense that you could almost see a thin string hanging over your head, waiting to make a sound. My Dad doesn't want to be apart from me, thinks we're making a big deal out of it, and he even makes me laugh by pressing his leg on my windowsill early in the morning.

But I understand his psychology. Sometimes you just can't imagine the worst, and you'd rather cross that option out of your head because it leads to an unbearable outcome. I read my cousin's temperature every day, ate, slept, and ate. I have never taken my medicine so regularly. My aunt sent me a message encouraging me, saying you are not Afraid Ah? I said, "No. ".

But how can you not be?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A lot of people are going through this. My High School Buddy's dad was in the hospital, and my dad's co-worker died because of the new crown. The shadows grow larger, closing in on everyone's circle, first from a distance, then from a distance, and finally from everyone. It's hard. I can't tell you more than that. Help if you can, but the power of the individual is small after all. My family was dying, and I had no way of getting help -- a real pain, a pain that made me ashamed, like the pain I felt from it was like plastic, a floating pollutant. But we have to look them in the eye and not look away.

A few nights ago at 8 o'clock, many residential areas in Wuhan spontaneously shouted Wuhan refueling, we open the window to listen, a variety of voices together, along the cold wind from the living room from this end to the other end. I was watching The Sun Also Rises, and the movie was coming to an end, and Zhou Yun was yelling, don't be afraid, he smiled and the sun came out. I've never been a big fan of group action, but at this critical juncture, a raw, active, sad emotion arises. I was captured by it.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The situation is grim. But stay positive. It's like the Chinese have always come this way.

There is a small lake near our house. My father always likes to go for a walk by the lake. Since his colleague died over new crown, he hasn't mentioned going for a walk by the lake. His shift has been extended to February 14th, with possible changes, and he is now snacking on sunflower seeds for the live news of the outbreak. This afternoon we stood by the window, watching the neighborhood cats roll around in the sun, and Magnolia denudata was even budding.

The beginning of spring is coming. I hope the good news comes with the beginning of spring.

By Liu Chenyu
